# Question-bank `.tex` files

`.tex` files under `public/tex/` are the **day-to-day editing surface** for question content. Brand-new topics are imported from Overleaf via `scripts/deploy-from-overleaf.mjs`, but ongoing fixes (typos, statement rewrites, mark adjustments, solution edits) happen here in the repo. The QBT pack (`qbt/_QBT__<Topic>.tex`) is the single source of truth for question statements; the matching solutions pack (`soln/_QBT___Solns__<Topic>.tex`) owns only the per-question Solution `tcolorbox`. See the QBT ⇄ SOLN contract below for the propagation tooling.

## Build layout

```
public/tex/**/qbt/
  _QBT__<Topic>.tex             ← source (tracked, hand-edited)
  _QBT__<Topic>.pdf             ← deployed PDF (tracked)
  build/
    _QBT__<Topic>.pdf           ← latexmk output, never edit
    aux/                        ← latexmk aux files, never edit

public/tex/**/soln/
  _QBT___Solns__<Topic>.tex     ← source (tracked, hand-edited)
  _QBT___Solns__<Topic>.pdf     ← deployed PDF (tracked)
  build/
    _QBT___Solns__<Topic>.pdf   ← latexmk output, never edit
    aux/                        ← latexmk aux files, never edit
```

PDFs inside `build/` (`public/tex/**/build/*.pdf`) are build outputs — **never read or edit them**. PDFs directly in `qbt/` or `soln/` are the deployed production files.

`scripts/lib/tex-utils.mjs` (`shouldProcessTexFile`) treats anything under `qbt/` or `soln/` (excluding `notes/`) as a tracked QBT/soln pack. That's the set the hygiene scripts operate on.

## Naming patterns

| Pattern | Meaning |
|---------|---------|
| `_QBT__<Topic>.tex` | Question pack |
| `_QBT___Solns__<Topic>.tex` | Solutions pack |
| `_Notes__<Title>.tex` (under `notes/`) | Standalone notes |

Filenames at first-import time are produced by `sanitizeTopic` (in `scripts/deploy-from-overleaf.mjs`), which replaces every non-alphanumeric character in the Overleaf project's topic name with an underscore. Don't rename files by hand after the fact — the filenames are referenced from `src/data/resources.ts`.

## QBT ⇄ SOLN statement contract

Every QBT/soln pair shares an identical per-question statement region. The QBT file is the **single source of truth** for question statements; the soln file's per-question block is shaped exactly:

```
% ---- Question N ----
\questionitem
<statement — byte-identical to the QBT block>

\vspace*{10pt}

\begin{tcolorbox}[colback=white, colframe=scarlet, title={\textbf{Solution}}, ...]
<solution body>
\end{tcolorbox}
```

The boundary is detected by the line containing both `\begin{tcolorbox}` and `title={\textbf{Solution}}`. QBT statements may themselves contain other tcolorboxes (e.g. info / working boxes) — only the `Solution`-titled one demarcates the statement / solution split.

Tooling:

- `scripts/check-questions.mjs` — read-only drift detector. Reports any pair where the SOLN statement region differs from the QBT statement, plus structurally broken pairs (mismatched `% ---- Question N ----` delimiter sets, duplicate delimiters). Wired into `.husky/pre-commit` and the `predev`/`prebuild`/`precheck` npm hooks. Non-zero exit on drift or structural break.
- `scripts/sync-questions.mjs` — rewrites SOLN statement regions in place to match QBT. Solution `tcolorbox` content and the `\vspace*{10pt}` prelude are preserved exactly. Skips structurally broken pairs (run `check-questions` first to triage; the fix for `qbt-only` / `soln-only` / `numbering-mismatch` is to hand-edit the missing or misnumbered `% ---- Question N ----` delimiter and `\questionitem`).
- `scripts/lib/question-blocks.mjs` — shared pure parser for both scripts. Tested in `scripts/lib/question-blocks.test.mjs`.

If the boundary detection or block shape changes (Solution `tcolorbox` signature, prelude shape, delimiter regex), update this section and `AGENTS.md`'s "QBT ⇄ SOLN statement contract" subsection together.

## `check-tex` body-comment hygiene

`scripts/check-tex.mjs` (run automatically by the husky pre-commit hook) lints the **document body** of every QBT/soln `.tex` file (between `\begin{document}` and `\end{document}`). It rejects any full-line comment **except** the canonical question delimiter inserted by `clean-tex`:

```latex
% ---- Question 1 ----
```

Any other full-line `% ...` line in the body is a violation. Inline comments after content (`\item foo % note`) are fine.

If `check-tex` flags a file, the usual fix is `npm run clean-tex` — it strips the offending comments, collapses runs of more than two blank lines down to two, and re-numbers the question delimiters.

## Local compilation

CI does **not** run `latexmk`, so any `.tex` edit that affects rendering needs the corresponding `.pdf` rebuilt and committed alongside it. Whitespace-only edits (e.g. those produced by `sync-questions` for cosmetic-only drift) typically don't change PDF bytes — `git status` will tell you.

For a single file:

```pwsh
latexmk -f -pdf -cd -interaction=nonstopmode -synctex=1 -file-line-error `
  -auxdir=<dir>/build/aux -outdir=<dir>/build <file.tex>
# then promote the built PDF up beside the source:
Copy-Item <dir>/build/<name>.pdf <dir>/<name>.pdf
```

For bulk: `npm run compile-tex [further-maths|tmua|all] [--deploy]`. The `--deploy` flag copies built PDFs up beside the source on success — that's the usual way to follow up a `sync-questions` run that touched many files.

The Overleaf import script (`npm run deploy-overleaf`) compiles automatically as part of first-time topic placement; once a topic is in the repo, `compile-tex --deploy` is the recompile path.
